{"id":"project-LICHEN-rpkd","title":"copy_fixed_string does not null-terminate destination","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshcore/adapter.c
Lines: 109-125 (copy_fixed_string)

The function copies a string to a fixed-size buffer without null-termination:
```c
static void copy_fixed_string(uint8_t *dst, size_t dst_len,
                  const char *fallback, const char *preferred)
{
    const char *src = (preferred != NULL && preferred[0] != '\0') ?
              preferred : fallback;
    size_t len;

    if (dst == NULL || dst_len == 0U || src == NULL) {
        return;
    }

    len = strlen(src);
    if (len > dst_len) {
        len = dst_len;  // Truncate
    }
    memcpy(dst, src, len);  // No null terminator added
}
```

The destination is NOT null-terminated. If src is shorter than dst_len, the remaining bytes in dst are left unchanged (could contain garbage).

Looking at callers:
- Line 196-197: copies into out[58] for 6 bytes (SELF_INFO_NAME_LEN)
- Line 234-242: copies into device_info buffer at various offsets

The protocol may expect null-terminated strings. If dst previously contained longer data, the caller would see garbage after the copied string.

The callers (enqueue_self_info, enqueue_device_info) zero-initialize their buffers:
```c
uint8_t out[LICHEN_MESHCORE_SELF_INFO_LEN] = {
    LICHEN_MESHCORE_RESP_SELF_INFO,
};
```

This zero-initializes the entire array, so remaining bytes are 0. The function is safe WITH this caller pattern, but the function itself is fragile - a future caller not zero-initializing would have problems.

Consider: either document the requirement, or have copy_fixed_string null-terminate or zero-pad.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:47:43.060902Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:47:43.06093Z"}
